            "chars": "<p dir=\"ltr\"><em>LD.VI.R10</em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\"><strong>Mrs Merdle &ndash; Bosom&nbsp;</strong></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Mrs. Merdle is referred to repeatedly as &ldquo;the bosom,&rdquo; a term that first appears in this chapter as a literal reference to her person (&ldquo;the breadth of bosom which seemed essential to her having room enough to be unfeeling in&rdquo; [LD 236]), but which becomes a synecdoche in the following chapter (&ldquo;The bosom, moving in Society with jewels displayed upon it, attracted general admiration&rdquo; [241]).&nbsp;</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\">Sucksmith identifies Mrs. Merdle as the likely manifestation of part of an early note in Dickens&rsquo;s book of&nbsp;<em>Memoranda</em>: &ldquo;Miss C.B. The enthusiastically complimentary person, who forgets you in her own flowery prosiness, as&ndash;&rsquo;I have no need to say to a person of your genius and feeling, and wide range of experience;&rsquo;&ndash;and then being&hellip; short-sighted puts up her glass, to remember who you are&rdquo; (<em>Memoranda</em>&nbsp;4; Sucksmith xxvii).&nbsp;</p>"
        }
    ],
